arXiv:2411.06592v1 Announce Type: new Abstract: In light of the recent branching fraction measurement of the $B^{+}	o K^{+} 
u ar{
u}$ decay by Belle II and its poor agreement with the SM expectation, we analyze the effects of an axion-like particle (ALP) in $B$ meson decays. We assume a long-lived ALP with a mass of the order of the pion mass that decays to two photons. We focus on a scenario where the ALP decay length is of the order of meters such that the ALP has a non-negligible probability to decay outside the detector volume of Belle II, mimicking the $B^{+}	o K^{+} 
u ar{
u}$ signal. Remarkably, such an arrangement is also relevant for the long-standing $B	o \pi K$ puzzle by noting that the measured $B^{0}	o \pi^{0}K^{0}$ and $B^{+}	o \pi^{0}K^{+}$ decays could have a $B^{0}	o a K^{0}$ and $B^{+}	o a K^{+}$ component, respectively. We also argue based on our results that the required ALP-photon effective coupling belongs to a region of parameter space that can be extensively probed in future beam dump experiments like SHiP.
